name: CompositeTemplate
title: Composite Templates: Custom Forms with Shared Signature Document
shortDescription: With composite templates, signers can fill out separate forms but complete the same signature document.
sampleFeatures:
This sample features

  • Composite templates
  • Envelopes
  • Embedded signing
  • Tabs
codeFlow:
Code flow

Step 1

A Templates:create call defines the server template, which specifies a document to be signed by two recipients.

The recipients definition in this call includes two placeholder recipients. The roleName and recipientId defined for each placeholder in this call will be used in the next call to associate the recipient with a name, email address, and other identifying information.

For each recipient, the server template includes a Sign Here tab and Date Signed tab.

Note: Every time you execute this scenario, it creates a new server template as a setup step. When developing your own integration, you would create server templates for each use case by using the eSignature web app or API requests, and then simply reuse the server templates when creating envelopes.

Step 2

An Envelopes:create request creates a compositeTemplates array and generates an envelope. The array elements are described in the sections below.

compositeTemplateId 1

Includes a document element, which specifies a document, and an inlineTemplate. The inline template overlays the document with tabs. Both the document and tabs are customized for the first signer.

compositeTemplateId 2

Like the previous item, this defines a document overlaid by an inline template with tabs. In this case, both are customized for the second signer.

compositeTemplateId 3

Incorporates the server template created in Step 1 to provide a shared signing document for both signers. The serverTemplates element is automatically populated with the templateId returned in the response to the Templates:create call.

The server template is overlaid with an inlineTemplate that uses a roleName and recipientId to associate each placeholder recipient from the previous call with a name, email address, and clientUserId. The clientUserId property indicates that this is an embedded signing transaction, which enables recipients to sign documents from within your app instead of accessing them via an email (known as remote signing).

Step 3

An EnvelopeViews:createRecipient request generates the first signer’s recipient signing URL, which is the page where you can sign the document. The clientUserId, signer name, and email in this call match the ones supplied for the first signer in the previous call. The envelopeId in this request is automatically populated with the ID returned in the response to the Envelopes:create call.

Step 4

As in the previous step, an EnvelopeViews:createRecipient request generates a recipient signing URL, but this URL is for the second signer.
description:
Scenario execution instructions

To execute API calls one by one

Select Step 1 in the left navigation and follow the instructions on the page.

To execute all API calls consecutively

Supply all required values in the Parameters section below and select Execute.

To execute all API calls multiple times

  1. Enter the number of executions in the Options section.
  2. Supply all required values in the Parameters section.
    Note: You can configure a parameter to have a unique value for each execution by inserting the text {random} or {iteration}, including the curly braces, anywhere in the value. At execution time, {random} will be replaced with a random number and {iteration} will be replaced with the number of the execution.
  3. Select Execute.

To display the server template

After executing step 1, or after executing the entire scenario, follow these steps to display the server template:

  1. Navigate to the eSignature web app Templates page.
  2. Check the Name column to find the server template you added.
  3. Select the button in that row to view the server template details or perform other operations.

To sign the documents

After executing steps 3 and 4, or after executing the entire scenario, follow these steps to navigate to the signing URL for each signer:

  1. If the API call execution list at the bottom of the screen is not displayed, click the API call execution tab to display it.
  2. Locate the row for the most recently executed step with step name CompositeTemplate_Step_3.
  3. In the Response body column for that row, copy the value of the url response parameter. Be sure to copy the entire value, which wraps to several lines. This is the signing URL for the first signer.
  4. In a new browser tab or window, paste the copied value into the browser’s URL field and press Enter. The signing URL is displayed, and you can sign the document.
    Note: After the signing URL has been generated, it remains active for five minutes and then expires.
  5. After signing, you’ll be redirected to a page that displays an event query parameter that indicates the outcome of the signing process.
  6. To complete the signing process for the second signer, locate the API call execution list row for the most recently executed step with step name CompositeTemplate_Step_4, and copy the URL from Response body column. Then paste it in a new browser tab as you did for the first signer’s URL.

steps.name: CompositeTemplate_Step_1
steps.title: Step 1: Create a server template
steps.description:
To execute this API call:

  1. Supply all parameter values below.
    Note: You can configure a parameter to have a unique value by inserting the text {random}, including the curly braces, anywhere in the value. At execution time, {random} will be replaced with a random number.
  2. Select Execute.
  3. (Optional) To display the server template:
    • Navigate to the eSignature web app Templates page.
    • Check the Name column to find the server template you added.
    • Select the button in that row to view the server template details or perform other operations.
  4. Select Next step to supply parameters for the next call and execute it.

parametersPrompts.name: name
parametersPrompts.title: Server template name
parametersPrompts.note: A unique name for the server template. This name is not visible to the envelope recipient. The server template is displayed under this name in the eSignature web app templates list.

parametersPrompts.name: description
parametersPrompts.title: Server template description
parametersPrompts.note: A brief description of the server template. This description is not visible to the envelope recipient. It is displayed when you select the Edit option for the server template in the eSignature web app templates list.

parameters.name: accountId
parameters.description: The external account number (int) or account ID GUID.
